function maxPrizes(prizePositions, k) {
    function bs(arr, x) {
        let l = 0, r = arr.length;
        while (l < r) {
            const m = Math.floor((l + r) / 2);
            if (arr[m] < x) l = m + 1;
            else r = m;
        }
        return l;
    }
    const n = prizePositions.length;
    let ans = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        const left_segment_end = prizePositions[i] + k;
        const right_segment_start = bs(prizePositions, left_segment_end + 1);
        const right_segment_end = prizePositions[right_segment_start] + k;
        ans = Math.max(ans, bs(prizePositions, right_segment_end + 1) - bs(prizePositions, prizePositions[i]));
    }
    return ans;
}
```

    The main idea of the algorithm is to iterate through each element `prizePositions[i]` and find the optimal segments for it. The first segment starts at `prizePositions[i]` and ends at `prizePositions[i] + k`. The second segment starts right after the first segment ends, and also has a length of `k`. We can then find the start and end of the second segment iteratively by using binary search (upper bound in C++, bisect_right in Python, Arrays.binarySearch in Java, and a custom `bs` function in JavaScript). The maximum number of prizes we can win is calculated by checking the difference between the leftmost and rightmost prize positions covered by the two optimal segments. The answer is the maximum value of this difference for all possible `prizePositions[i]`.

